@dm sy In 2014, when Russia attacked Ukraine, many lost their homes in the East and understand this text without a secret meaning. There are a lot of comments from them.

It's a kind of poetry that is very hard to translate retaining all layers of meaning. The main theme here is ambivalence about  belonging. Yaroslav Serhieiev I agree that โclassโ is more frequently used in this meaning and, maybe, more logical. But itโs a song, a poetry. And a poetry is a kind of art. Art is generally perceived more with emotions than with logical thinking. Different people may see various meanings in the same art work.
โGradeโ in my mind is associated with something that is classified by degree of some quality. โClassโ is just a group of people (or things) with one similar peculiarity. 
In accord with my way of understanding this song, it shows the modern life as structured system in which people work like inanimate robots in the skyscrapers. When I heard ยซะ ัะฐะฝะดะตะผั ะทั ัะฒะพัะผะธ ะฒะธัะพัะบะฐะผะธ ะ ััะตััะพะณะพ, ััะพะผะพะณะพ ะณะตััะฐะผะธ-ะณะตััะฐะผะธยป, I imagined it like graduation of the social ladder: the higher sit a person - the better rung he or she has. 
But this graduation donโt change the fact that people are stuck in their โcombsโ and they donโt truly enjoy their life.
As for the lexical consistency, I have checked it in Context Reverso and found that โgradeโ is also can be used in this meaning.
